  <axiom component="lesson-plan">
      <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
      <dl>
        <li>
          <title>Suggested Time</title>
          <p>15 minutes</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Objective</title>
          <p>To discover the rules for combining surds through grouping similar terms.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <title>Teacher's Role</title>
          <p>Guide learners to compare adding surds to adding algebraic variables. Use a calculator to demonstrate that <m>\sqrt{2} + \sqrt{3} \neq \sqrt{5}</m>.</p>
        </li>
      </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>Working in pairs, consider the following expressions and use your knowledge of <q>like terms</q> to answer the questions:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>If you have 3 bags of <m>\sqrt{5}</m> and your friend gives you 2 more bags of <m>\sqrt{5}</m>, how many total bags do you have?</li>
          <li>Use a calculator to find the value of <m>\sqrt{9} + \sqrt{16}</m>. Is the answer equal to <m>\sqrt{25}</m>?</li>
          <li>Can you simplify <m>5\sqrt{2} + 3\sqrt{7}</m> into a single term? Explain your reasoning.</li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </activity>
